00:47:53.410 --> 00:47:56.310
We've created some
that are very specific,

00:47:56.310 --> 00:47:59.410
for example, the ones that are
looking at international trade

00:47:59.410 --> 00:48:03.040
data, some that are growing to
become less specific and more

00:48:03.040 --> 00:48:03.700
general.

00:48:03.700 --> 00:48:05.725
For instance, DataViva
started looking only

00:48:05.725 --> 00:48:07.080
at industrial data for Brazil.

00:48:07.080 --> 00:48:08.905
Now it also includes
location data,

00:48:08.905 --> 00:48:10.640
and we're even
looking to incorporate

00:48:10.640 --> 00:48:14.410
even environmental
data in the future.

00:48:14.410 --> 00:48:15.957
So what I want to
do next is I want

00:48:15.957 --> 00:48:18.290
to validate some of the
theories that I told you before.

00:48:18.290 --> 00:48:20.812
This is the idea that
economies are computers

00:48:20.812 --> 00:48:23.623
and that the computational
capacity of these computers

00:48:23.623 --> 00:48:26.170
is determined by their ability
to form networks that they

00:48:26.170 --> 00:48:28.163
can use to model computation.

00:48:28.163 --> 00:48:30.680
And that eventually,
we can use this theory

00:48:30.680 --> 00:48:34.800
to explain differences in
income and economic growth.

00:48:34.800 --> 00:48:36.550
And to be able to
validate those theories,

00:48:36.550 --> 00:48:38.758
I first have to make sure
that we're on the same page

00:48:38.758 --> 00:48:42.440
according to a very
important relationship, which

00:48:42.440 --> 00:48:44.970
is the relationship within
genotypes and phenotypes.

00:48:44.970 --> 00:48:48.310
So a genotype is the information
that is encoded in your genes.

00:48:48.310 --> 00:48:51.060
A phenotype is a trait
that is observable

00:48:51.060 --> 00:48:53.200
to an external observer.

00:48:53.200 --> 00:48:55.820
So in principle, obviously,
you can genotype people

00:48:55.820 --> 00:48:59.370
by sequencing, but
sequencing is kind of hard.

00:48:59.370 --> 00:49:02.010
And also, figuring out
what genes are associated

00:49:02.010 --> 00:49:05.040
to which traits is kind of
difficult. So in some sense,

00:49:05.040 --> 00:49:06.640
one thing that we
can do is let's say

00:49:06.640 --> 00:49:11.080
I'm curious about the genes
that encode for height.

00:49:11.080 --> 00:49:14.615
And I have two people, Danny
DeVito and LeBron James.

00:49:14.615 --> 00:49:16.925
Obviously, one
cumbersome way of trying

00:49:16.925 --> 00:49:19.174
to figure out who has the
genes that encode for height

00:49:19.174 --> 00:49:20.517
would be to sequence
them and try

00:49:20.517 --> 00:49:23.058
to figure out what are the many
genes that encode for height.

00:49:23.058 --> 00:49:25.930
There are known to be more or
less more than 10 genes maybe

00:49:25.930 --> 00:49:27.450
that encode height.

00:49:27.450 --> 00:49:30.362
Or the other thing is I can just
look at Danny DeVito and LeBron

00:49:30.362 --> 00:49:31.780
James and say, hey,
probably LeBron James

00:49:31.780 --> 00:49:33.321
has genes that encode
for being tall,

00:49:33.321 --> 00:49:35.674
and Danny DeVito doesn't
have those genes.

00:49:35.674 --> 00:49:38.866
So in some sense, even if I
don't have a technology that

00:49:38.866 --> 00:49:40.486
allows me to look
at the genotypes,

00:49:40.486 --> 00:49:42.236
I can know a lot about
a person's genotype

00:49:42.236 --> 00:49:43.238
by looking at their
phenotype because

00:49:43.238 --> 00:49:45.010
of the genotype-phenotype
relationship.

00:49:45.010 --> 00:49:49.718
By the same token, economies are
computers that run on knowledge

00:49:49.718 --> 00:49:50.559
and know how.

00:49:50.559 --> 00:49:52.850
And measuring knowledge and
know how is very difficult.

00:49:52.850 --> 00:49:54.475
So I can look at
knowledge and know how

00:49:54.475 --> 00:49:57.970
by looking at the products
that economies make.

00:49:57.970 --> 00:50:00.702
So if an economy produces
cars and produces good cars,

00:50:00.702 --> 00:50:02.740
I know something about
the fact that they

00:50:02.740 --> 00:50:05.630
know how to shape metal and
they have mechanical engineers.

00:50:05.630 --> 00:50:07.546
In a company like Google,
I know that you guys

00:50:07.546 --> 00:50:10.060
know how to deal with data
and to build websites.

00:50:10.060 --> 00:50:12.436
In a company like Apple,
I know that they're

00:50:12.436 --> 00:50:14.310
very good at consumer
products and the design

00:50:14.310 --> 00:50:15.610
of those products.

00:50:15.610 --> 00:50:18.255
So in some way, what
I want to do now

00:50:18.255 --> 00:50:20.440
is I want to look at
the mix of products

00:50:20.440 --> 00:50:22.650
that a country or a
region makes as a way

00:50:22.650 --> 00:50:24.752
to try to understand
the type of knowledge

00:50:24.752 --> 00:50:26.153
and know how that they have.

00:50:26.153 --> 00:50:28.038
I'm going to in some
way measure the capacity

00:50:28.038 --> 00:50:31.050
of a computer
based on the output

00:50:31.050 --> 00:50:34.510
that it's able to produce.

00:50:34.510 --> 00:50:37.110
So I'm going to look
at a number of facts

00:50:37.110 --> 00:50:39.545
because obviously,
no rope of evidence

00:50:39.545 --> 00:50:41.114
is built on a single strand.

00:50:41.114 --> 00:50:43.650
And the first fact that
I'm going to look at

00:50:43.650 --> 00:50:45.950
is at the structure of
the network that connects

00:50:45.950 --> 00:50:47.640
industries to locations.

00:50:47.640 --> 00:50:49.480
So here on the left,
I have a network

00:50:49.480 --> 00:50:51.580
that connects municipalities
and industries.

00:50:51.580 --> 00:50:53.520
These are all
municipalities in Chile.

00:50:53.520 --> 00:50:55.570
On the right, I have
a network that's

00:50:55.570 --> 00:50:57.820
connecting countries to the
products that they export.

00:50:57.820 --> 00:51:00.710
A black dot represents
a link, meaning

00:51:00.710 --> 00:51:04.320
that an industry is present in
that municipality or a product

00:51:04.320 --> 00:51:06.307
is being exported
by that country.

00:51:06.307 --> 00:51:08.140
And these matrices are
not sorted at random.

00:51:08.140 --> 00:51:10.570
On the top, I put the most
diverse municipalities

00:51:10.570 --> 00:51:12.070
or the most diverse countries.

00:51:12.070 --> 00:51:15.937
And on the left, I put the
most ubiquitous industries,

00:51:15.937 --> 00:51:17.770
the ones that are present
in most locations,

00:51:17.770 --> 00:51:19.673
or the most ubiquitous
products, the ones

00:51:19.673 --> 00:51:21.890
that are exported by the
largest number of countries.

00:51:21.890 --> 00:51:24.120
And what you see is that
this matrix is nested.

00:51:24.120 --> 00:51:27.540
Nestedness is a
pattern that was first

00:51:27.540 --> 00:51:31.000
discovered by an ecologist
looking at insular habitats.

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:33.220
If you have islands
of increasing size,

00:51:33.220 --> 00:51:35.894
the ecosystems of those
islands become more diverse,

00:51:35.894 --> 00:51:38.560
but it also becomes more diverse
in discovering nested patterns.

00:51:38.560 --> 00:51:41.160
Because I think that is--
islands of increasing size

00:51:41.160 --> 00:51:44.940
are also more sophisticated
ecological computers.

00:51:44.940 --> 00:51:46.760
And what this
nested pattern tells

00:51:46.760 --> 00:51:49.034
you is that where the places
that produce few things,

00:51:49.034 --> 00:51:50.950
they don't produce a
random set of few things.

00:51:50.950 --> 00:51:52.575
They produce subsets
of the things that

00:51:52.575 --> 00:51:54.036
are produced by more places.

00:51:54.036 --> 00:51:55.966
And they produce
subsets of the ones that

00:51:55.966 --> 00:51:57.492
are produced by more places.

00:51:57.492 --> 00:51:59.031
This is not a
[INAUDIBLE] matrix,

00:51:59.031 --> 00:52:00.280
but it's like a nested matrix.

00:52:00.280 --> 00:52:01.770
They are subsets.

00:52:01.770 --> 00:52:04.475
And this nestedness is at first
strand in the rope of evidence

00:52:04.475 --> 00:52:07.121
because it tells you, well, the
places that are little diverse

00:52:07.121 --> 00:52:08.620
are places, obviously,
that can only

00:52:08.620 --> 00:52:10.525
form relatively
small networks that

00:52:10.525 --> 00:52:11.930
are unsophisticated computers.

00:52:11.930 --> 00:52:14.014
And the places that
are more diverse,

00:52:14.014 --> 00:52:16.442
they can produce large
networks that are

00:52:16.442 --> 00:52:17.650
more sophisticated computers.

00:52:17.650 --> 00:52:20.260
And they can produce
the things that

00:52:20.260 --> 00:52:22.010
are done by the
unsophisticated computers,

00:52:22.010 --> 00:52:25.000
but also the ones
that are done only

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:26.230
in a sophisticated computer.

00:52:26.230 --> 00:52:30.230
So if you think about it,
think of an Atari 2600.

00:52:30.230 --> 00:52:31.822
An Atari 2600 by
today's standards

00:52:31.822 --> 00:52:33.280
is a very
unsophisticated computer.

00:52:33.280 --> 00:52:36.244
And you can run Pac-Man on it.

00:52:36.244 --> 00:52:38.220
Now, on my Mac, I
can also run Pac-Man,

00:52:38.220 --> 00:52:41.690
but I can run things that I
cannot run on an Atari 2600.

00:52:41.690 --> 00:52:43.360
So in some sense, the
more sophisticated

00:52:43.360 --> 00:52:44.860
the computer, the
more diverse it's

00:52:44.860 --> 00:52:47.364
going to be able
to have as input.

00:52:47.364 --> 00:52:49.280
But also, it's going be
able to produce inputs

00:52:49.280 --> 00:52:51.660
that are very rare,
that it would only

00:52:51.660 --> 00:52:54.585
be able to produce in very
sophisticated computers.

00:52:54.585 --> 00:52:56.710
So that's the first strand
in the rope of evidence.

00:52:56.710 --> 00:53:00.430
The second strand goes
into ideas of learning.

00:53:00.430 --> 00:53:05.010
So according to some computers,
just like you, me, and cells,

00:53:05.010 --> 00:53:09.340
and computers, in some
way, they need to learn.

00:53:09.340 --> 00:53:10.885
Sometimes, the way
that computers is

00:53:10.885 --> 00:53:12.290
that we don't let them learn.

00:53:12.290 --> 00:53:14.980
We just tell them what to do.

00:53:14.980 --> 00:53:16.741
But someone has to
do the learning.

00:53:16.741 --> 00:53:19.974
And economies as computers, they
learn at this collective level.

00:53:19.974 --> 00:53:22.015
And what happens is that
one property of learning

00:53:22.015 --> 00:53:23.597
is that it's always
easier to learn

00:53:23.597 --> 00:53:25.180
something that is
similar to something

00:53:25.180 --> 00:53:27.640
that you already know.

00:53:27.640 --> 00:53:29.820
So if I know Spanish, it's
relatively easy for me

00:53:29.820 --> 00:53:32.760
to learn Portuguese and it's
hard for me to learn Chinese,

00:53:32.760 --> 00:53:38.207
not because Portuguese might be
inherently easier than Chinese,

00:53:38.207 --> 00:53:39.804
but simply because
I have knowledge

00:53:39.804 --> 00:53:41.470
that is very similar
and very redundant.

00:53:41.470 --> 00:53:42.915
A lot of words I
can simply reuse.

00:53:42.915 --> 00:53:44.915
A lot of grammar I can
simply reuse from Spanish

00:53:44.915 --> 00:53:46.956
to Portuguese, but I cannot
reuse it from Spanish

00:53:46.956 --> 00:53:48.500
to Chinese.

00:53:48.500 --> 00:53:51.266
And economies is some
way do the same thing.

00:53:51.266 --> 00:53:54.284
So they diversity towards
related varieties.

00:53:54.284 --> 00:53:56.575
What that means is that if
you know the mix of products

00:53:56.575 --> 00:53:58.850
that a country makes, you
can very accurately predict

00:53:58.850 --> 00:54:01.330
the mix of products that
it's going to make next.

00:54:01.330 --> 00:54:03.970
So here, I have a picture of the
product space for Chile, 1979.

00:54:03.970 --> 00:54:07.500
So what does this picture mean?

00:54:07.500 --> 00:54:12.070
Each dot represents a product,
and the dots that are painted

00:54:12.070 --> 00:54:14.730
are the products that Chile
exported in the year 1979.

00:54:14.730 --> 00:54:16.575
The ones that are
gray, like fresh fish,

00:54:16.575 --> 00:54:20.530
are products that Chile did
not export in that year.

00:54:20.530 --> 00:54:21.840
Now we have links.

00:54:21.840 --> 00:54:24.060
The links are proportional
to the property

00:54:24.060 --> 00:54:25.942
that two products
are co-exported.

00:54:25.942 --> 00:54:27.900
So if I know that two
products are co-exported,

00:54:27.900 --> 00:54:29.896
I know that they must
be kind of similar.

00:54:29.896 --> 00:54:31.270
Because I know
that, for example,

00:54:31.270 --> 00:54:32.936
the countries that
export preserved fish

00:54:32.936 --> 00:54:34.350
tend to export fresh fish.

00:54:34.350 --> 00:54:36.180
I can predict that
since Chile already

00:54:36.180 --> 00:54:38.470
knows how to export
preserved fish, crustaceans,

00:54:38.470 --> 00:54:41.120
and mollusks, and
frozen fish, they

00:54:41.120 --> 00:54:43.810
might become good at exporting
fresh fish in the future.

00:54:43.810 --> 00:54:46.520
By the same token, if I go to
this other part of the product

00:54:46.520 --> 00:54:50.770
space and I look at, say, parts
of metalworking machine tools,

00:54:50.770 --> 00:54:54.830
that's a product that Chile
is not producing anything

00:54:54.830 --> 00:54:56.638
that is related to that.

00:54:56.638 --> 00:54:58.660
So learning how to
produce that product

00:54:58.660 --> 00:55:00.910
would be very difficult
because we have nothing

00:55:00.910 --> 00:55:03.322
that we could reuse.

00:55:03.322 --> 00:55:05.030
So now I'm going to
fast forward in time.

00:55:05.030 --> 00:55:09.970
So we're in 1979 and I'm
going to go to the year 1996.

00:55:09.970 --> 00:55:12.590
If I go to the year 1996, I
see that Chile now also exports

00:55:12.590 --> 00:55:15.676
fresh fish and also
exports frozen fish filets

00:55:15.676 --> 00:55:17.260
that they didn't export before.

00:55:17.260 --> 00:55:20.200
And they diversified in this
part of the product space that

00:55:20.200 --> 00:55:21.690
was the part of
the product space

00:55:21.690 --> 00:55:24.834
that was close to the part
that they were already in.

00:55:24.834 --> 00:55:27.204
And this is something that
is actually true in general.

00:55:27.204 --> 00:55:29.329
You guys probably here are
familiar with ROC curves

00:55:29.329 --> 00:55:31.060
when you're doing a
prediction algorithm.

00:55:31.060 --> 00:55:33.270
The product space has
a [INAUDIBLE] of 0.5

00:55:33.270 --> 00:55:34.290
in an ROC curve.

00:55:34.290 --> 00:55:35.660
You're trying to predict
the mix of products

00:55:35.660 --> 00:55:37.201
that a country is
going to make next.

00:55:37.201 --> 00:55:39.971
So this is actually quite
accurate at predicting

00:55:39.971 --> 00:55:41.570
the mix of products
that a country

00:55:41.570 --> 00:55:42.260
is going to make in the future.

00:55:42.260 --> 00:55:44.270
Obviously, there's a
shitload of false positives,

00:55:44.270 --> 00:55:45.575
too, because the process
of diversification

00:55:45.575 --> 00:55:46.825
has very future positives.

00:55:46.825 --> 00:55:49.960
But ROC curves are
still very good.

00:55:49.960 --> 00:55:53.880
So the second string
on our rope of evidence

00:55:53.880 --> 00:55:56.330
is the fact that
economies learn by moving

00:55:56.330 --> 00:55:59.403
into related varieties.

00:55:59.403 --> 00:56:01.236
The third string relates
to economic growth.

00:56:01.236 --> 00:56:03.170
And the idea of economic
growth is an old idea

00:56:03.170 --> 00:56:07.050
that we can say started
with a Scotsman, Adam Smith.

00:56:07.050 --> 00:56:08.510
And he conceptualized
the economy

00:56:08.510 --> 00:56:11.060
in terms of two things,
capital and labor.

00:56:11.060 --> 00:56:11.960
Labor were people.

00:56:11.960 --> 00:56:14.380
Capital were things
that people did.

00:56:14.380 --> 00:56:17.260
And then people saved the things
that they did to produce things

00:56:17.260 --> 00:56:17.940
in the future.

00:56:17.940 --> 00:56:19.773
And those ideas were
eventually mathematized

00:56:19.773 --> 00:56:21.540
by Robert Solow in the 1950s.

00:56:21.540 --> 00:56:23.998
And what happened is that when
Solow advanced these models,

00:56:23.998 --> 00:56:25.750
there was a big
gap that was left.

00:56:25.750 --> 00:56:30.344
That gap was between the
model and the empirical data.

00:56:30.344 --> 00:56:31.885
And that gap
eventually, other people

00:56:31.885 --> 00:56:35.965
tried to explain it by using
information on other factors

00:56:35.965 --> 00:56:38.390
that they thought that
Solow had left out.

00:56:38.390 --> 00:56:40.650
So for instance, in
the '80s and '90s,

00:56:40.650 --> 00:56:43.808
people like [? Robert ?]
Mankiw and Paul [? Robert ?]

00:56:43.808 --> 00:56:46.550
started to introduce the
idea of human capital.

00:56:46.550 --> 00:56:47.950
It's not just people and things.

00:56:47.950 --> 00:56:50.210
People have to know things also.

00:56:50.210 --> 00:56:53.410
And then people in
the '90s and 2000s,

00:56:53.410 --> 00:56:55.370
they started to
include social capital.

00:56:55.370 --> 00:56:57.000
People might know things,
but if they're all assholes

00:56:57.000 --> 00:56:58.570
and they don't
talk to each other

00:56:58.570 --> 00:57:01.360
and they don't get
along well, eventually,

00:57:01.360 --> 00:57:04.390
what's going to happen is
that that's not going to work.

00:57:04.390 --> 00:57:06.410
So people need to come together.

00:57:06.410 --> 00:57:07.910
And social capital
is another factor

00:57:07.910 --> 00:57:09.200
that was not being accounted.

00:57:09.200 --> 00:57:10.699
And when they
included human capital

00:57:10.699 --> 00:57:12.285
and they included
social capital,

00:57:12.285 --> 00:57:14.354
the gap that Solow
had left behind

00:57:14.354 --> 00:57:16.210
started to shrink a little bit.

00:57:16.210 --> 00:57:18.530
The models were doing
better and better.

00:57:18.530 --> 00:57:21.450
But also, now that we understand
that economies are computers,

00:57:21.450 --> 00:57:23.299
we can try to reinterpret
all of these ideas

00:57:23.299 --> 00:57:24.840
and try to see if
there was something

00:57:24.840 --> 00:57:27.070
that is still missing.

00:57:27.070 --> 00:57:30.250
So now, within that we
have two firms here.

00:57:30.250 --> 00:57:33.270
We can start to reinterpret
all of these factors

00:57:33.270 --> 00:57:35.400
in terms of the [INAUDIBLE]
that I've introduced.

00:57:35.400 --> 00:57:37.140
On the one hand,
firms produce things.

00:57:37.140 --> 00:57:39.610
And I think that this is
physical capital or crystals

00:57:39.610 --> 00:57:41.920
of imagination.

00:57:41.920 --> 00:57:43.830
On the other hand, we
can think that people

00:57:43.830 --> 00:57:46.980
need to know things,
and that's engineered

00:57:46.980 --> 00:57:48.696
knowledge or human capital.

00:57:48.696 --> 00:57:50.566
People need to
collect, and that's

00:57:50.566 --> 00:57:52.350
social capital and trust.

00:57:52.350 --> 00:57:54.350
But what is missing
from this picture

00:57:54.350 --> 00:57:56.400
is something else,
which is the knowledge

00:57:56.400 --> 00:57:58.400
and know how that the
systems accumulate

00:57:58.400 --> 00:57:59.674
at the collective level.

00:57:59.674 --> 00:58:01.340
And that is different
than the knowledge

00:58:01.340 --> 00:58:03.589
and know how that people
have at the individual level.

00:58:03.589 --> 00:58:05.315
And that's what is missing.

00:58:05.315 --> 00:58:08.485
But we can figure
out what societies

00:58:08.485 --> 00:58:10.410
or what economies
have accumulated

00:58:10.410 --> 00:58:11.994
vast amounts of
knowledge and know how

00:58:11.994 --> 00:58:14.368
at the collective level by
looking at the mix of products

00:58:14.368 --> 00:58:17.640
that they make, and that's what
I call learning complexity.

00:58:17.640 --> 00:58:19.250
So using the information
on the matrix

00:58:19.250 --> 00:58:20.980
that I've got of
countries and products,

00:58:20.980 --> 00:58:23.769
and taking some [INAUDIBLE]
measures out of it,

00:58:23.769 --> 00:58:26.310
we can actually create measures
of the computational capacity

00:58:26.310 --> 00:58:27.540
of economies.

00:58:27.540 --> 00:58:31.116
And these measures are not only
highly correlated with income

00:58:31.116 --> 00:58:33.490
per capita, but the deviations
between these correlations

00:58:33.490 --> 00:58:36.186
are predictors of
future economic growth.

00:58:36.186 --> 00:58:37.727
So for example, a
country like China,

00:58:37.727 --> 00:58:40.463
that you would see
down here, is a country

00:58:40.463 --> 00:58:43.160
that in 1985 had a
computational capacity that

00:58:43.160 --> 00:58:45.980
was much larger than what would
be expected by its income.

00:58:45.980 --> 00:58:47.055
So it was doomed to grow.

00:58:47.055 --> 00:58:49.835
A country like Greece had
an income that was too high,

00:58:49.835 --> 00:58:51.210
given its
computational capacity,

00:58:51.210 --> 00:58:53.001
so it was going to have
problems sustaining

00:58:53.001 --> 00:58:54.792
that level of income.

00:58:54.792 --> 00:58:58.161
So actually, when we think
about economies as computers,

00:58:58.161 --> 00:59:00.660
we realize that the level of
income that an economy achieves

00:59:00.660 --> 00:59:04.260
tends to converge to the
computational capacity.

00:59:04.260 --> 00:59:06.650
Moreover, actually,
economic complexity

00:59:06.650 --> 00:59:08.548
is a very good
explanatory factor

00:59:08.548 --> 00:59:10.770
when you're trying to
explain income inequality.

00:59:10.770 --> 00:59:12.470
Just to go very
briefly here, if you

00:59:12.470 --> 00:59:14.220
take two countries
like Chile and Malaysia

00:59:14.220 --> 00:59:16.921
that have basically the
same level of income

00:59:16.921 --> 00:59:19.450
and the same level of
education, if you want

00:59:19.450 --> 00:59:22.270
to try to explain why Chile
is more unequal than Malaysia,

00:59:22.270 --> 00:59:23.980
you can explain that
very well if you

00:59:23.980 --> 00:59:26.153
look at the mix of
products that Chile makes

00:59:26.153 --> 00:59:27.944
vis a vis the products
that Malaysia makes.

00:59:27.944 --> 00:59:30.610
And this is because the mix of
products that a country makes

00:59:30.610 --> 00:59:33.000
tend to co-evolve
with the institutions.

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:35.110
So imagine you were
trying to run Google

00:59:35.110 --> 00:59:38.590
as people used to run tobacco
plantations in the 1700s.

00:59:38.590 --> 00:59:42.140
Probably, it would not work
because those were companies

00:59:42.140 --> 00:59:45.715
that had very exploitative
institutions that did not

00:59:45.715 --> 00:59:47.255
consider ways in
which they could

00:59:47.255 --> 00:59:49.213
incorporate the knowledge,
know how, creativity

00:59:49.213 --> 00:59:50.270
of their workers.

00:59:50.270 --> 00:59:52.180
But for the tobacco
industry, in some sense,

00:59:52.180 --> 00:59:54.845
that kind of worked because
it was a very simple industry.

00:59:54.845 --> 00:59:56.340
Now when you have
something that is much more

00:59:56.340 --> 00:59:57.820
complex in which you
have to include people,

00:59:57.820 --> 01:00:00.465
eventually, you have to discover
the institutions that can

01:00:00.465 --> 01:00:02.450
make your company productive.

01:00:02.450 --> 01:00:04.325
And those institutions
for complex industries

01:00:04.325 --> 01:00:07.570
tend to be institutions
that are very inclusive.

01:00:07.570 --> 01:00:11.165
So the way that we behave
also is shaped and co-evolves

01:00:11.165 --> 01:00:15.730
with the type of
things that we do.

01:00:15.730 --> 01:00:20.025
I'm going to skip this part,
even though it's so nice.

01:00:20.025 --> 01:00:22.169
So another thing that
we can use to try

01:00:22.169 --> 01:00:24.460
to understand the computational
capacities of economies

01:00:24.460 --> 01:00:26.418
and systems is not by
looking only at products,

01:00:26.418 --> 01:00:28.390
but by looking at
cultural production.

01:00:28.390 --> 01:00:31.545
Because you can think of
the United States as a place

01:00:31.545 --> 01:00:34.385
that exports soybeans
and cars and jet engines,

01:00:34.385 --> 01:00:36.169
or you can think of
the United States

01:00:36.169 --> 01:00:38.335
as the birthplace of Miles
Davis and Neil Armstrong.

01:00:38.335 --> 01:00:40.740
And in some way, that
second description,

01:00:40.740 --> 01:00:44.272
I would say, is very
important and is very valid.

01:00:44.272 --> 01:00:45.980
So what we started
doing a few years ago,

01:00:45.980 --> 01:00:48.420
we started to collect data
on cultural production

01:00:48.420 --> 01:00:52.420
to try to understand the rate
at which our society remembers

01:00:52.420 --> 01:00:55.255
things and the types of
things that we remember,

01:00:55.255 --> 01:00:57.120
and how those are
affected by technology.

01:00:57.120 --> 01:00:58.850
So here, what we have is two
charts with two different data

01:00:58.850 --> 01:00:59.349
sets.

01:00:59.349 --> 01:01:01.230
The one on the top is
the Pantheon data set,

01:01:01.230 --> 01:01:03.606
and this is data that
includes every person that

01:01:03.606 --> 01:01:06.118
has a presence in more
than 25 different languages

01:01:06.118 --> 01:01:07.755
in Wikipedia.

01:01:07.755 --> 01:01:10.270
So you have to be
famous in 25 languages.

01:01:10.270 --> 01:01:13.150
You have to be globally famous
to be part of that data set.

01:01:13.150 --> 01:01:15.715
And what we see on the
y-axis is the probability

01:01:15.715 --> 01:01:17.650
that one of these
globally famous people

01:01:17.650 --> 01:01:20.770
was born in a year as a
fraction of the population

01:01:20.770 --> 01:01:23.010
of the world in that year.

01:01:23.010 --> 01:01:27.230
And you see that basically,
that line jiggles

01:01:27.230 --> 01:01:31.270
in what is statistically
proven Gaussian noise

01:01:31.270 --> 01:01:33.210
until the printing
press comes along.

01:01:33.210 --> 01:01:35.220
And then there's a
discontinuity and it jumps,

01:01:35.220 --> 01:01:36.619
and it goes to another state.

01:01:36.619 --> 01:01:38.702
And then the Industrial
Revolution comes, and then

01:01:38.702 --> 01:01:41.100
it jumps again, and
it keeps on jumping.

01:01:41.100 --> 01:01:43.000
Now, this the Human
Accomplishment Data Set,

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:46.620
which is a compendium of 4,000
historically famous biographies

01:01:46.620 --> 01:01:48.190
published in the year 2003.

01:01:48.190 --> 01:01:51.680
It's a much smaller data set,
but we find the same pattern

01:01:51.680 --> 01:01:53.133
and the same transition points.

01:01:53.133 --> 01:01:56.031
And what this is telling us is
that changes in communication

01:01:56.031 --> 01:01:58.790
technology are changing the
capacity of our computer

01:01:58.790 --> 01:02:01.180
to remember collectively.

01:02:01.180 --> 01:02:03.650
Before writing, we all
remembered nothing.

01:02:03.650 --> 01:02:06.450
Nobody knows the name of anybody
that was born 20,000 years ago.

01:02:06.450 --> 01:02:08.720
Then with the
invention of writing,

01:02:08.720 --> 01:02:10.440
we started to record
some information.

01:02:10.440 --> 01:02:12.120
And then with the
invention of printing,

01:02:12.120 --> 01:02:14.429
the amount of information
that we were able to record

01:02:14.429 --> 01:02:15.220
started to explode.

01:02:15.220 --> 01:02:17.120
And now with modern [INAUDIBLE]
technology, obviously,

01:02:17.120 --> 01:02:19.100
we have moved from a
world in which history

01:02:19.100 --> 01:02:22.740
used to be something that was
reserved only for the elite

01:02:22.740 --> 01:02:25.240
to a world in which everyone
has a personal history hidden

01:02:25.240 --> 01:02:30.180
in the metadata that you guys
and other companies also have.

01:02:30.180 --> 01:02:32.680
Also, [INAUDIBLE] technology
changed the type of information

01:02:32.680 --> 01:02:34.980
that we produce.

01:02:34.980 --> 01:02:37.280
So if you look at the era
of writing, pre-printing,

01:02:37.280 --> 01:02:39.995
you will see that most
of the famous people that

01:02:39.995 --> 01:02:42.370
are recorded in our data set
are either political figures

01:02:42.370 --> 01:02:44.140
or religious figures.

01:02:44.140 --> 01:02:45.830
But when the printing
press comes along,

01:02:45.830 --> 01:02:48.246
these measures of cultural
production change dramatically.

01:02:48.246 --> 01:02:51.220
And now you have famous
scientists and famous artists

01:02:51.220 --> 01:02:54.067
that become globally provocative
because the printing press did

01:02:54.067 --> 01:02:56.200
not only change the number
of books that produce.

01:02:56.200 --> 01:02:58.199
But it also changed what
those books were about.

01:02:58.199 --> 01:02:59.696
And if you're
interested in that,

01:02:59.696 --> 01:03:02.330
the best reference there is
Elizabeth Eisenstein's "The

01:03:02.330 --> 01:03:05.900
Printing Press as
an Agent of Change."

01:03:05.900 --> 01:03:08.934
But the printing press obviously
was not the last revolution.

01:03:08.934 --> 01:03:10.600
When film and radio
came along, the arts

01:03:10.600 --> 01:03:11.970
shifted dramatically
because what

01:03:11.970 --> 01:03:14.344
happened is that the arts
transformed into something that

01:03:14.344 --> 01:03:17.425
was about performance, not about
the creation of pieces anymore.

01:03:17.425 --> 01:03:20.388
So before film and radio,
the ones that become famous

01:03:20.388 --> 01:03:22.239
was the painter or the composer.

01:03:22.239 --> 01:03:23.822
After the invention
of film and radio,

01:03:23.822 --> 01:03:26.200
it's the actor, the
musician, the singer

01:03:26.200 --> 01:03:29.040
because the new medium
that was invented there

01:03:29.040 --> 01:03:32.520
recorded the performance,
and that changed [INAUDIBLE].

01:03:32.520 --> 01:03:34.650
And then when
television comes along,

01:03:34.650 --> 01:03:37.288
now you invent the
famous sports figure.

01:03:37.288 --> 01:03:40.250
[INAUDIBLE] these things are
causal because obviously,

01:03:40.250 --> 01:03:42.375
for instance, if you look
at the ability of actors,

01:03:42.375 --> 01:03:44.380
there were actors at
the times of the Greeks,

01:03:44.380 --> 01:03:45.165
and there were
actors, obviously,

01:03:45.165 --> 01:03:47.450
at the time of Shakespeare
that interpret and perform

01:03:47.450 --> 01:03:48.374
his plays.

01:03:48.374 --> 01:03:49.915
But the actors were
not the ones that

01:03:49.915 --> 01:03:51.039
became famous at that time.

01:03:51.039 --> 01:03:53.200
They were the playwrights
until we developed

01:03:53.200 --> 01:03:55.782
a medium in which
the performance was

01:03:55.782 --> 01:03:57.551
the one that was recorded.

01:03:57.551 --> 01:03:59.550
So I started by telling
you that the universe is

01:03:59.550 --> 01:04:03.364
made of three things, energy,
matter, and information,

01:04:03.364 --> 01:04:05.280
and that information
is the one that

01:04:05.280 --> 01:04:06.717
makes the universe interesting.

01:04:06.717 --> 01:04:10.116
Information endows the universe
with its structure, its beauty,

01:04:10.116 --> 01:04:12.080
and its complexity.

01:04:12.080 --> 01:04:14.019
I argue that there's
three mechanisms that

01:04:14.019 --> 01:04:16.310
help us explain the existence
and growth of information

01:04:16.310 --> 01:04:18.458
despite the second
law of thermodynamics.

01:04:18.458 --> 01:04:21.222
The first one is that
information is not free.

01:04:21.222 --> 01:04:23.430
You need to spend some energy
to produce information.

01:04:23.430 --> 01:04:25.590
The second one is
that you need to have

01:04:25.590 --> 01:04:28.052
ways to store that
information, and solids are

01:04:28.052 --> 01:04:29.669
an excellent way of doing it.

01:04:29.669 --> 01:04:32.740
And finally, matter needs
to develop this capacity

01:04:32.740 --> 01:04:33.471
to compute.

01:04:33.471 --> 01:04:34.970
And this capacity
to compute is what

01:04:34.970 --> 01:04:36.335
is most important
because it's what

01:04:36.335 --> 01:04:37.918
make the growth of
knowledge possible,

01:04:37.918 --> 01:04:41.435
but also what makes it difficult
because computation always

01:04:41.435 --> 01:04:43.900
needs to be physically
embodied, and the systems

01:04:43.900 --> 01:04:48.020
that embody computation are
always of finite capacity.

01:04:48.020 --> 01:04:50.100
And the only way that
those systems transcend

01:04:50.100 --> 01:04:55.800
that finite capacity
is by actually creating

01:04:55.800 --> 01:04:57.630
social structures
that allow them

01:04:57.630 --> 01:05:01.184
to act as parallel
computers, as computers

01:05:01.184 --> 01:05:03.600
that are able to process things
socially and collectively.

01:05:03.600 --> 01:05:06.540
So the cell transcends its
limitation by multicellularity.

01:05:06.540 --> 01:05:08.380
And multicellularity
eventually takes

01:05:08.380 --> 01:05:10.116
us all the way to the human.

01:05:10.116 --> 01:05:11.810
But then the human
is also limited.

01:05:11.810 --> 01:05:14.622
In order for us to increase
our computational capacities

01:05:14.622 --> 01:05:16.746
and make information grow,
we have to create teams,

01:05:16.746 --> 01:05:18.435
we have to create
firms, and we have

01:05:18.435 --> 01:05:20.430
to create networks
of [INAUDIBLE], which

01:05:20.430 --> 01:05:23.072
are increasingly larger
social and economic computers

01:05:23.072 --> 01:05:26.940
that help push the
growth of information

01:05:26.940 --> 01:05:28.410
to what we have until today.

01:05:28.410 --> 01:05:30.660
And obviously, it will
keep on pushing the growth

01:05:30.660 --> 01:05:31.870
of information in the future.

01:05:31.870 --> 01:05:33.870
And with that, I
would like to thank

01:05:33.870 --> 01:05:35.570
you very much for
your time and I'm

01:05:35.570 --> 01:05:36.732
happy to take any
questions you might have.

01:05:36.732 --> 01:05:37.232
Thank you.

