01:07:22.165 --> 01:07:24.110
and how there might
be interaction

01:07:24.110 --> 01:07:27.775
between social policies
and economic prosperity.

01:07:27.775 --> 01:07:29.400
So for instance, in
the past, we tended

01:07:29.400 --> 01:07:32.775
to have institutions that
were very discriminatory that

01:07:32.775 --> 01:07:35.620
limit our ability to perform
connections between people

01:07:35.620 --> 01:07:38.350
from different ethnicities,
from different nationalities,

01:07:38.350 --> 01:07:40.715
from different genders.

01:07:40.715 --> 01:07:43.484
And those policies, we would
say they were hurting us.

01:07:43.484 --> 01:07:45.900
And it's good that we're moving
in this opposite direction

01:07:45.900 --> 01:07:50.950
because that helps increase
computational capacity that

01:07:50.950 --> 01:07:54.210
helps information grow, and
eventually economies grow.

01:07:54.210 --> 01:07:57.300
Also, you have these very
simple and very obvious

01:07:57.300 --> 01:08:00.170
policy applications, but
that can be derived easily

01:08:00.170 --> 01:08:03.320
from the fact that economies
are computers that are embodied

01:08:03.320 --> 01:08:04.170
on social networks.

01:08:08.508 --> 01:08:10.918
AUDIENCE: On your
economic complexity chart,

01:08:10.918 --> 01:08:11.882
you have countries.

01:08:11.882 --> 01:08:13.328
Could you apply
that to companies

01:08:13.328 --> 01:08:15.720
as well, where companies
might diversify?

01:08:15.720 --> 01:08:18.920
CESAR HIDALGO: So that's a good
question because in some sense,

01:08:18.920 --> 01:08:22.279
as you have this
re-quantization of computation,

01:08:22.279 --> 01:08:24.090
you're going to
have matrices that

01:08:24.090 --> 01:08:26.090
have different
structure along the way.

01:08:26.090 --> 01:08:28.584
So for instance, if you
think about a country,

01:08:28.584 --> 01:08:30.239
a country is a very
large computer.

01:08:30.239 --> 01:08:32.540
It's a very large unit that
includes lots of people.

01:08:32.540 --> 01:08:36.000
It includes networks of firms
and organizations and so forth.

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:39.137
In that case, the push is
going to be towards diversity.

01:08:39.137 --> 01:08:41.095
But if you start looking
at simpler and simpler

01:08:41.095 --> 01:08:43.220
and simpler, smaller
computers and smaller systems,

01:08:43.220 --> 01:08:45.479
then the finite size
of those systems

01:08:45.479 --> 01:08:47.370
pushes towards specialization.

01:08:47.370 --> 01:08:51.019
So if I look at a company, like
Google doesn't do everything.

01:08:51.019 --> 01:08:53.685
And they shouldn't do everything
because there's a lot of things

01:08:53.685 --> 01:08:54.880
that you guys are good at,
and there's other things

01:08:54.880 --> 01:08:56.130
that you guys are not good at.

01:08:56.130 --> 01:08:58.510
So in some sense, you might
want to stay out of things

01:08:58.510 --> 01:08:59.790
that you're not good at
and focus on the things

01:08:59.790 --> 01:09:01.050
that you're good at,
and maybe discover

01:09:01.050 --> 01:09:03.479
new things that you might
be good at that leverage

01:09:03.479 --> 01:09:04.830
your capacities.

01:09:04.830 --> 01:09:07.859
So in that case, the
measures, I would say,

01:09:07.859 --> 01:09:11.120
do not apply immediately.

01:09:11.120 --> 01:09:12.760
But I don't think
that it would be

01:09:12.760 --> 01:09:15.985
impossible to create measures
that would take that data

01:09:15.985 --> 01:09:19.223
and would be inspired by this
idea of economic complexity

01:09:19.223 --> 01:09:20.639
and computation
to create measures

01:09:20.639 --> 01:09:22.270
of the capacities of firms.

01:09:30.617 --> 01:09:32.581
AUDIENCE: I guess
another similar question.

01:09:32.581 --> 01:09:36.000
I was thinking if you tend
to maybe think strategies

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:42.504
that countries have adopted
to enable themselves to grow

01:09:42.504 --> 01:09:46.345
as computers, as in the
amount of information

01:09:46.345 --> 01:09:47.094
that they produce.

01:09:47.094 --> 01:09:49.198
Because obviously, a
company might [INAUDIBLE]

01:09:49.198 --> 01:09:52.446
diversification
because [INAUDIBLE].

01:09:52.446 --> 01:09:56.790
But have there been any
other ways in which countries

01:09:56.790 --> 01:10:00.480
have tried to diversify
their production of goods

01:10:00.480 --> 01:10:05.620
or historically proven
ways that-- again,

01:10:05.620 --> 01:10:09.340
things that they haven't been
doing well they start to do.

01:10:09.340 --> 01:10:11.800
I guess that's pretty much it.

01:10:11.800 --> 01:10:14.970
Or is one of the components that
were presented that contributes

01:10:14.970 --> 01:10:16.470
towards the
potential information

01:10:16.470 --> 01:10:18.960
growth in a country,
if one of them

01:10:18.960 --> 01:10:20.344
is easier to modify than others.

01:10:20.344 --> 01:10:24.290
Because obviously, for
example, social links,

01:10:24.290 --> 01:10:26.450
predefined social links
like family connections

01:10:26.450 --> 01:10:28.130
are not easy to
modify, like you said.

01:10:28.130 --> 01:10:28.850
CESAR HIDALGO:
And in most cases,

01:10:28.850 --> 01:10:31.016
obviously, one thing is
that you understand society.

01:10:31.016 --> 01:10:33.601
Another thing is that
you can engineer it.

01:10:33.601 --> 01:10:35.272
The same is true,
for instance, if you

01:10:35.272 --> 01:10:36.980
think about Darwin's
theory of evolution.

01:10:36.980 --> 01:10:40.140
You can develop a very
deep understanding of where

01:10:40.140 --> 01:10:41.352
biological order comes from.

01:10:41.352 --> 01:10:43.732
But going from Darwin's
theory of evolution

01:10:43.732 --> 01:10:45.629
to genetic engineering
is a big step.

01:10:45.629 --> 01:10:47.920
By the same token, I do think
that in our understanding

01:10:47.920 --> 01:10:50.020
of social economic
systems, we're

01:10:50.020 --> 01:10:54.410
just starting to realize that
these systems are computers.

01:10:54.410 --> 01:10:56.882
And we have a pretty deep
understanding of them

01:10:56.882 --> 01:10:59.840
that does not allow
us to engineer them.

01:10:59.840 --> 01:11:01.319
One of the things
that I do think,

01:11:01.319 --> 01:11:03.120
though, is that sometimes,
the question, for example,

01:11:03.120 --> 01:11:05.540
that you're asking now might
be a little bit of a trick

01:11:05.540 --> 01:11:08.980
question because you think
that economies are computers.

01:11:08.980 --> 01:11:12.480
Maybe the existence of countries
is kind of like a bad idea.

01:11:12.480 --> 01:11:14.950
In some sense,
what you want to do

01:11:14.950 --> 01:11:17.370
is increase the computational
capacity of the planet

01:11:17.370 --> 01:11:20.020
and the prosperity
of all people.

01:11:20.020 --> 01:11:24.745
And countries are kind of like
a barrier for that to happen.

01:11:24.745 --> 01:11:26.120
Nowadays, for
instance, one thing

01:11:26.120 --> 01:11:28.786
that I found ridiculous-- I'm an
anti-nationalist about nations.

01:11:28.786 --> 01:11:31.690
And as an anti-nationalist
about nations,

01:11:31.690 --> 01:11:34.710
I find it ridiculous
that even though we

01:11:34.710 --> 01:11:37.210
have learned that you should
not discriminate people because

01:11:37.210 --> 01:11:39.930
of things that
they do not choose,

01:11:39.930 --> 01:11:43.590
like your ethnicity
or your gender,

01:11:43.590 --> 01:11:45.830
we still accept and
encourage discrimination

01:11:45.830 --> 01:11:48.445
based on the color of
people's passports.

01:11:48.445 --> 01:11:51.220
And that's bullshit,
and that's a barrier

01:11:51.220 --> 01:11:54.340
to the organization of people
into more efficient computers.

01:11:54.340 --> 01:11:58.770
So maybe the best way to
help countries prosper

01:11:58.770 --> 01:12:02.150
is to get rid of these
divisions between countries

01:12:02.150 --> 01:12:06.010
in a much more global context.

01:12:06.010 --> 01:12:09.515
Obviously, sometimes those
really soothing effects

01:12:09.515 --> 01:12:12.130
are going to mean that
there's some people that now,

01:12:12.130 --> 01:12:14.244
because of some
protective measure,

01:12:14.244 --> 01:12:15.660
are doing better
than they should.

01:12:15.660 --> 01:12:17.402
And those people are
not going to want

01:12:17.402 --> 01:12:18.568
that type of redistribution.

01:12:18.568 --> 01:12:20.520
But I think that
over the long run,

01:12:20.520 --> 01:12:23.362
it might be more fair
and better for everyone.

01:12:34.448 --> 01:12:35.700
AUDIENCE: I was just curious.

01:12:35.700 --> 01:12:38.560
According to this measure
of economic complexity

01:12:38.560 --> 01:12:42.199
as a predictor of a country's
future economic growth, which

01:12:42.199 --> 01:12:45.073
countries are likely to
have strong economic growth

01:12:45.073 --> 01:12:46.031
in our future?

01:12:46.031 --> 01:12:49.863
Which countries currently
have the biggest disparity

01:12:49.863 --> 01:12:53.130
between economic complexity and
the current economic status?

01:12:53.130 --> 01:12:55.532
CESAR HIDALGO: So there
is some obvious candidates

01:12:55.532 --> 01:12:58.340
that everybody is aware
of, like China and India,

01:12:58.340 --> 01:13:02.428
some a little bit less obvious,
like Vietnam, and some,

01:13:02.428 --> 01:13:05.880
for example, that have a
lot of growth potential

01:13:05.880 --> 01:13:09.230
but at the moment have
very low levels of income.

01:13:09.230 --> 01:13:12.145
So in some sense,
the growth is not

01:13:12.145 --> 01:13:14.770
going to translate into
those countries becoming

01:13:14.770 --> 01:13:16.040
large economic powers.

01:13:16.040 --> 01:13:19.182
But it's going to be substantial
nevertheless, like countries

01:13:19.182 --> 01:13:20.390
in East Africa, for instance.

01:13:20.390 --> 01:13:22.015
East Africa has
managed to become

01:13:22.015 --> 01:13:24.925
a little bit more
industrialized than West Africa.

01:13:24.925 --> 01:13:26.870
And that industrialization
of East Africa

01:13:26.870 --> 01:13:27.790
that happened--
the garden center

01:13:27.790 --> 01:13:30.373
with the export of flowers, with
other products that they have

01:13:30.373 --> 01:13:35.856
been able to develop, as we see
that, it's implying that now,

01:13:35.856 --> 01:13:37.460
the level of income
of East Africa

01:13:37.460 --> 01:13:39.085
should start approaching
more like that

01:13:39.085 --> 01:13:42.490
of Latin America than the
one that they have right now.

01:13:42.490 --> 01:13:44.385
So those would be
a few examples.

01:13:44.385 --> 01:13:47.670
Countries that are
on the opposite side,

01:13:47.670 --> 01:13:49.400
obviously, we can
mention Greece,

01:13:49.400 --> 01:13:51.863
but I think Greece already
gets too much of a bad rap here

01:13:51.863 --> 01:13:52.363
in Europe.

01:13:52.363 --> 01:13:55.920
You guys should
give them a break.

01:13:55.920 --> 01:13:57.420
You have all of
the countries that

01:13:57.420 --> 01:13:58.670
export a lot of raw materials.

01:13:58.670 --> 01:14:00.711
So all of the countries
that export raw materials

01:14:00.711 --> 01:14:03.540
are reliers on the relationship
because their income

01:14:03.540 --> 01:14:07.016
is pegged to the national
resource endowments.

01:14:07.016 --> 01:14:10.160
So countries like Saudi
Arabia or Qatar or Chile,

01:14:10.160 --> 01:14:13.090
or even Australia, if
they were to run out

01:14:13.090 --> 01:14:15.136
of natural resources,
or if the economy

01:14:15.136 --> 01:14:17.510
were to change in such a way
that the resources that they

01:14:17.510 --> 01:14:21.370
export is no longer needed,
it would be in deep trouble

01:14:21.370 --> 01:14:23.700
because their computers
are not as sophisticated

01:14:23.700 --> 01:14:27.000
as their income would suggest.

